# lib/consultation-gate.allowlist — SP15 T-2 (Plan 71 SP15)
#
# Foundational-decision surface allowlist for consultation_propose.
#
# Surfaces NOT listed here that invoke consultation_propose return rc=2 and
# emit a {action: "consult-blocked", reason: "not-allowlisted"} audit-log
# entry. Prevents per-action gate creep — consultation fires only at
# foundational/structural decisions; per-artifact preview stays on the
# existing 3-step gate.
#
# Modifying this file requires peter_diff_review on the modifying task
# (SP15 spec L53; tasks.md T-2 AC4).
#
# RATIONALE
# ---------
# Consent fatigue (Q4 finding): repeated approval prompts degrade meaningful
#   sign-off. When gates fire on every action users habituate and rubber-stamp
#   them, hollowing out the very approval signal the gate was built to capture.
#   Implication: gate only at structural/foundational decisions; never per-
#   artifact. Sources:
#     Secure Privacy — understanding consent fatigue and best practices
#       https://secureprivacy.ai/blog/understanding-consent-fatigue-and-best-practices
#     CHI 2024 dark-patterns survey — override fatigue in approval UX
#       https://arxiv.org/html/2405.07378v1
#
# Boehm cost-of-change + schema-migration cost: structural decisions retrofitted
#   late consume 50-70% of migration project effort. Late-fixed defects cost up
#   to 100x per Boehm's 1981 curve; modern reanalysis flattens but does not
#   zero the asymmetry. Implication: foundational decisions earn an upfront
#   consultation step precisely because their late-correction cost is
#   asymmetric vs. early sign-off. Sources:
#     Boehm cost-of-change curve (1981)
#       https://www.researchgate.net/figure/Historical-cost-to-fix-curve-Adapted-from-Boehm-1981-p-40_fig11_308264787
#     DataFlowMapper — data-migration cost analysis (50-70% pre-migration share)
#       https://dataflowmapper.com/blog/data-migration-costs-quantitative-analysis
#
# Status-quo bias: users develop documented preference for the existing state
#   over change, even when the existing state is suboptimal — gates therefore
#   earn their place at decisions where post-hoc edits are expensive AND the
#   bias against later fixes is documented. This is the SP15 selection
#   criterion for what enters this allowlist. Source:
#     CHI 2024 PMC review — status-quo bias in HCI
#       https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11375477/
#
# Audit lineage:
#   spec.md L53 (T-2 description) +
#   _audit-2026-05-03/11-sp15-spawn-decision.md §"Consent fatigue / override
#   fatigue", §"Boehm cost-of-change", §"Status-quo bias", §"Mandatory
#   architectural constraints" item 2.
#
# FORMAT: one surface-id per line; exact match (no globs); blank lines and
# `#`-prefixed comments ignored.
#
# ALLOWLIST
surface-3-vault-claude-md
surface-4-tag-prefixes
surface-6-frontmatter-enforce
sp13-stage-2-5-import-plan
